data.content:
## What breaks in .NET 11

In EF Core 11 (Cosmos DB provider), the **sync-over-async opt-in is removed entirely**. All synchronous LINQ operations — `ToList()`, `First()`, `Count()`, `SaveChanges()` — will **throw `InvalidOperationException` at runtime**.

The Cosmos DB SDK is inherently async-only. EF Core 10 deprecated sync calls but allowed an opt-in; EF Core 11 drops that escape hatch.

## Fix: convert to async

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

**Key changes:**
- Return types become `Task<T>` / `Task`
- Methods become `async` and use `await`
- Sync LINQ operators → async counterparts (`ToListAsync`, `FirstAsync`, `CountAsync`, `SaveChangesAsync`)
- Convention: suffix method names with `Async`

**Note:** This is a viral change — every caller up the chain must also become async, all the way to the controller action. Make sure your controllers return `Task<IActionResult>` (or `Task<ActionResult<T>>`) as well.
